Abstract
There is an increasing availability of Ô¨Çoating car data both historic, in the form of trajectory
datasets and real-time, in the form of continuous data streams. This paves the way for several
advanced traÔ¨Éc management services such as current traÔ¨Éc state estimation, congestion and
incident detection and prediction of the short-term evolution of traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çow. In this paper, we
present an analysis of using probe vehicles for reconstructing traÔ¨Éc state. We employ detailed
agent-based microscopic simulations of a real world expressway to estimate the state from
Ô¨Çoating car data. The probe penetration required for accurate traÔ¨Éc state estimation is also
determined.
Keywords: TraÔ¨Éc state estimation, Simulation and modelling of transportation systems, Agent-based
simulations

1

Introduction

Floating cars refer to moving probe vehicles which act as traÔ¨Éc sensors by providing information
regarding their position Œ± (in terms of coordinates) and speed vŒ± at regular intervals. The
locations provided via GPS receivers can be map-matched to roads on a map. In turn this mapmatched data can be used to reconstruct traÔ¨Éc state constituting the macroscopic quantities
density œÅ, Ô¨Çow Q and local speed V¬Ø . Identifying regions of uniform Ô¨Çow and density will help
determine traÔ¨Éc patterns of interest such as jams, stop-and-go waves and changes in traÔ¨Éc
Ô¨Çow especially in the face of events such as accidents. In this paper we develop a methodology
for aggregating Ô¨Çoating car data (FCD) for accurate traÔ¨Éc state reconstruction. The minimum
probe penetration required for determining the traÔ¨Éc state is also determined by simulating
diÔ¨Äerent traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çow regimes on a real world expressway.
Reconstruction of traÔ¨Éc state in real-time using FCD (in the form of data streams) will also
enable initializing data driven traÔ¨Éc simulations for short term predictions of Ô¨Çow. This can
lead to a symbiotic traÔ¨Éc simulation platform [2] where the simulation system beneÔ¨Åts from
