the real time data provided by the physical system (the road network) which in turn beneÔ¨Åts
through mechanisms such as dynamic ramp metering and congestion aware routing [15].
Reconstructing traÔ¨Éc state from probe vehicles has been previously discussed in papers such
as [10, 8] and [6]. In this work we attempt to determine traÔ¨Éc density and Ô¨Çow traditionally
computed through stationary devices such as loop detectors [3] and video cameras [4], using
FCD. Towards this end the contributions of this paper are 1. A methodology for obtaining aggregated macroscopic (speed, density and Ô¨Çow) quantities
from the microscopic FCD consisting of (Œ±, vŒ± ).
2. An estimation of the minimum percentage of probe vehicles required for the macroscopic
traÔ¨Éc state reconstruction under diÔ¨Äerent traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çow regimes.

2

Existing Work

Using FCD as a means for estimating travel times and traÔ¨Éc state has received much attention
over the years. Papers such as [6] and [12] compute the average travel time on roads from the
average speed of the probes on that road. Techniques such as artiÔ¨Åcial neural networks are used
for short term predictions by using weighted aggregates of the past patterns [6]. While using
the trajectories of probe vehicles to detect events such as congestion and accidents has been
discussed in [1].
The percentage of probe vehicles required for reliable travel-time estimation has been discussed in papers such as [5] and [8]. The work in [10] is concerned with estimating the
percentage of probe vehicles for accurately determining the travel-time across the road-network
links. Based on numerical simulations (details of the simulation model are not provided), the
authors conclude that 1.5% penetration of probe vehicles are needed for accurate travel time
estimation.
While the authors of [8] estimate the probe penetration (to be around 2%) and the sampling
period to maximize traÔ¨Éc information by determining traÔ¨Éc time and space correlations. Two
spots are correlated in space if the correlation of average speeds in both the spots exceeds
a threshold. Thus, the traÔ¨Éc condition in a spot without measurements can be estimated if
the condition in a correlated spot is known, thus inÔ¨Çuencing probe penetration. Likewise the
correlation time measures the period over which the traÔ¨Éc conditions remain correlated in a spot
hence inÔ¨Çuencing the sampling period. The traÔ¨Éc time and space correlations were measured
using microscopic simulations. The details of the simulation parameters are not provided.
Similarly [5] deÔ¨Ånes conÔ¨Ådence intervals for accuracy in terms of average speed and travel
times across the links apart from spatial coverage as a function of probe penetration. The
authors conclude that 3% to 5% probe penetration is suÔ¨Écient for conÔ¨Ådence levels of 90% and
above.
To the best of our knowledge, there have been no attempts made at estimating traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çow
and density from FCD. This is generally due to the papers focusing mainly upon estimating
travels times from FCD which is in contrast to the requirements of a symbiotic traÔ¨Éc simulation
platform requiring knowledge of the current state in terms of œÅ, Q and V¬Ø . Further, most employ
macroscopic models which do not take into account the heterogeneous driving characteristics
and vehicle lengths and instabilities arising due to lane changes. This results in optimistic
conclusions on the minimum probe penetration required. In this work we show that, provided
suÔ¨Écient probe penetration, the traÔ¨Éc state constituting average speed and more importantly
density (and Ô¨Çow) can be reliably measured.
