Methodology

For determining the methodology for spatial aggregation of FCD and the minimum probe
penetration for accurate traÔ¨Éc state estimation, we employ agent-based microscopic traÔ¨Éc
simulations. Microscopic simulations of real world expressway were employed owing to lack of
real-world Ô¨Çoating car data.
Once the (Œ±, vŒ± ) pairs for the road stretch simulated is obtained, an algorithm for partitioning the FCD is required for determining the aggregated values of traÔ¨Éc density and in turn,
the Ô¨Çow. In order to do this, the partitioned regions must be microscopically large enough
to contain suÔ¨Écient samples of (Œ±, vŒ± ) pairs and be macroscopically small to determine traÔ¨Éc
patterns of interest such as congestion and variations in Ô¨Çow [14].
The Ô¨Årst method for spatial aggregation evaluated, naively divides the expressway into
uniform chunks of size 1.0 km each resulting in 13 segments in total. The second method
evaluated makes use of the topology of the expressway and divides it into segments between
on/oÔ¨Ä ramp pairs. The Ô¨Ånal approach divides the expressway into M segments such that
the variance of the speeds within all segments are minimized. Formally, the goal is to Ô¨Ånd
sections S1 , ... , SJ that minimize the total variance of the speeds given by

J
j=1 i‚ààSj

(vi ‚àí V¬ØSJ ).

Where V¬ØSJ represents the average speed in section Sj . This computationally hard optimization
problem (due to the inÔ¨Ånite number of ways in which the expressway can be divided into J
sections) is solved using a top down greedy approach known as recursive binary splitting [9].
The constructed binary tree is split until a minimum of 10 samples are present in each leaf
node. The tree so grown is pruned (to prevent over-Ô¨Åtting) using cost-complexity pruning [9].
The eÔ¨Écacy for spatial aggregation is determined based on the best model Ô¨Åt that can be
obtained for œÅ as a function of V¬Ø . To quantify the reliability of the model, we make use of the
R2 Statistic. This metric used henceforth in this paper is a measure of model Ô¨Åt in the form of
a proportion of variance explained by the model [9]. It takes a value between 0.0 and 1.0 and a
value close to 1.0 indicates that a large proportion of the variability in the density is explained
by the predictor, which in this case is the speed V¬Ø .
Once the relationship between œÅ and V¬Ø is established, we look at quantifying the accuracy of
traÔ¨Éc state estimation as a function of probe vehicle penetration for diÔ¨Äerent traÔ¨Éc conditions.
This helps to determine the minimum probe penetration required.

4

Experiments

Microscopic models describe traÔ¨Éc from the perspective of individual driver-vehicle units
(DVUs). These high-Ô¨Ådelity simulations should ideally capture heterogeneities in traÔ¨Éc in
terms of diÔ¨Äerent vehicle classes (e.g. cars, trucks) and driver behaviors (e.g. intelligent, aggressive). Further, the microscopic simulations employed for this study also model stochastic
lane changes thus helping to reconstruct the spatiotemporal state of traÔ¨Éc with far greater
accuracy in comparison to macroscopic models. The movement of driver-vehicle units are characterized by acceleration models for longitudinal motion and lane change models for lateral
movement along the road. In this section, we provide the details of our microscopic simulation
and of the real world expressway in Singapore we simulate.
2010

TraÔ¨Éc State Estimation Using Floating Car Data

4.1

Sunderrajan, Viswanathan, Cai and Knoll

TraÔ¨Éc Simulation

The traÔ¨Éc simulation we have employed, is based on the SEMSim platform [16]. SEMSim is a
high Ô¨Ådelity agent-based microscopic simulation. It uses the Intelligent Driver Model (IDM) [13]
and MOBIL [11] as the acceleration and lane change models respectively.
The IDM is an accident free model which ensures that a vehicle attains the desired velocity
at free Ô¨Çow and maintains the safe bumper to bumper distance to the leading vehicle. It also
ensures that the acceleration is an increasing function of the speed and distance to the leading
vehicle and a decreasing function of its speed. MOBIL, the lane change model ensures that the
resultant accelerations and decelerations for a vehicle and its followers in the old and new lanes
does not exceed a safe threshold. A lane change is done only if a vehicle gains speed without
violating the safety and inconvenience (to the old and new followers) criteria.
The simulation takes as input a road network detailing the lanes constituting the roads to
be simulated. Road segments that don‚Äôt have a preceding road segment are considered sources
and those without a subsequent segment are sinks. The traÔ¨Éc thus Ô¨Çows from the sources
to the sinks. Vehicles are created at each source as a Poisson process based on the equation
nextT imes = ‚àílnU
Œªs . The parameter nextT imes represents the time of arrival of a vehicle on a
source road s. The mean inter-arrival time for s (in seconds) is given by Œªs . The parameter U
is a random number between 0 and 1. The mean inter-arrival times Œªs of vehicles on a source
link s controls the average vehicle density on all roads simulated. It represents the expected
value of the number of agents entering the simulation via a source road. The route taken by
each DVU is determined based on static turn ratios speciÔ¨Åed at each intersection. Other inputs
to the simulation include time, number of agents and probability distribution of other model
parameters.

