5

Results

In this section, we reconstruct the macroscopic traÔ¨Éc state of P.I.E by aggregating the speed
proÔ¨Åles of probe vehicles based on the three diÔ¨Äerent spatial aggregation techniques discussed
in Section 3. We also determine the minimum probe penetration required for accurate traÔ¨Éc
state estimation.

5.1

Spatial Aggregation of FCD

Figure 4a shows the plot of œÅ(in vehicles/km) as function of V¬Ø when the P.I.E is divided into
equal sized segments of length 1.0km. The method does not take into account the topography
of P.I.E nor does it try to identify regions with a homogeneous distribution of speeds. While
Figure 4b shows the œÅ vs V¬Ø graph by aggregating FCD based on the 25 road segments comprising
the P.I.E stretch simulated. Both the Ô¨Ågures clearly establish an exponential relationship (based
on the linear regression Ô¨Åt) between V¬Ø and œÅ despite signiÔ¨Åcant bias.
The recursive binary partitioning approach (Section 3), divides P.I.E into homogeneous
partitions (numbering 12 in this case) based on the speed proÔ¨Åles of probe vehicles. Figure 4c
further establishes the exponential relationship between œÅ and V¬Ø with much lesser noise in
comparison to splitting using the two aforementioned approaches. The exponential relationship
between œÅ and V¬Ø in agreement with the Underwoods‚Äôs exponential model [7]. We thus Ô¨Åt a
linear model as shown in Equation 1 for estimating traÔ¨Éc density from average speed. The
coeÔ¨Écients Œ≤0 and Œ≤1 are the least squares coeÔ¨Écient estimates for linear regression.
œÅ = Œ≤0 + Œ≤1 √ó log(V¬Ø )

(1)

In the next section we show that the recursive binary splitting approach is the better method
for spatial aggregation of the (Œ±, vŒ± ) pairs considering lesser levels of probe penetration.

