period to around 15 seconds signiÔ¨Åcantly reduces the computational resources required for realtime map matching and traÔ¨Éc state reconstruction.

6

Conclusions and Future Work

In this work we have established that reliably estimating traÔ¨Éc state and more speciÔ¨Åcally
density (and thereby Ô¨Çow) on an expressway can be achieved with a minimum of 5% to 10%
probe vehicles depending upon the prevailing traÔ¨Éc conditions. Microscopic traÔ¨Éc simulations
reveal that recursive binary partitioning can be used to subdivide a stretch of road to identify
homogeneous regions of Q, œÅ and V¬Ø .
In the future, we would like to investigate if the results obtained on a relatively homogeneous
expressway can be replicated on signalized urban street networks. Future work would also
involve optimizing the minimum variance partitioning of the road network to automatically
detect onset of congestion and anomalous events such as accidents based on statistical learning
methods. Accurate estimation of speed, density and Ô¨Çows along important roads can help
initialize data driven simulations for short term predictions of the evolution of traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çows.
Predictive simulations will play a major role in enhancing the capabilities of dynamic control
strategies such as ramp metering and routing for traÔ¨Éc Ô¨Çow optimization.

